<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54144d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54144d">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54144d"> 144(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pots souls <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54144d"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Chez les Gabin (une de ces tribus), il a trouv&eacute; de ces symboles ou substituts qui repr&eacute;sentent non pas des morts, mais des vivants. &laquo;Beaucoup de Gabin semblent regarder ce pot comme leur propre double, comme le s&eacute;jour de leur &acirc;me... En cons&eacute;quence, c&apos;est un usage commun qu&apos;un jeune homme qui a fond&eacute; un foyer demande &agrave; un ami de fabriquer un pot pour lui, afin qu&apos;il puisse y mettre son &acirc;me en d&eacute;p&ocirc;t. Le jeune homme se couche par terre, et le potier s&apos;assied aupr&egrave;s de lui, donnant &agrave; l&apos;argile une forme qui est suppos&eacute;e ressembler au sujet.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Il est donc &eacute;vident qu&apos;ils regardent <mark>ces pots comme des doubles de l&apos;&acirc;me</mark> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <br><font color="green">[Among the Gabins (one of these tribes), he found these symbols or substitutes which represent not the dead, but the living. "Many Gabins seem to regard this pot as their own double, as the abode of their soul &hellip; Consequently, it is a common custom that a young man who has founded a home asks a friend to make a pot for him, so that he can put his soul there. The young man lies down on the ground, and the potter sits beside him, giving the clay a shape which is supposed to resemble the subject. [&hellip;]</font> It is therefore obvious that they regard these pots as duplicates of the soul] <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 217f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
